<td valign=top > 
<b> Image-Guided Neurosurgery </b>
<BR>
<p>
Magnetic resonance (MR) and computed tomography (CT) images provide a
detailed 3-D description of patient anatomy.  During neurosurgery it
is often desirable to establish a correspondence between these
pre-operative images and real-time images of the patient (as shown to
the right).  In so doing, the position of a surgical target (e.g., a
tumor), clearly visible in the MR or CT image, can be more easily
visualized by the surgeon.

<BR><BR>

We have developed a system that allows for the real-time overlay of
pre-operative MR or CT imagery onto a surgeon's operating microscope
view.  To accomplish this, our system estimates the transformation
between the pre-operative image space and the continually changing
surgical space - this estimation must be accurate to within 1 mm.

<BR><BR>

<i>(Collaborative work with Hai Sun and <a
href="http://engineering.dartmouth.edu/thayer/faculty/keithpaulsen.html">Keith
Paulsen</a>)</i>

